  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions against money laundering. These instruments aim to establish a global framework for combating money laundering and terrorist financing by promoting international cooperation, setting standards for national laws, and encouraging the establishment of financial intelligence units (FIUs). Here are some of the key international instruments:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This convention was one of the earliest international efforts to address money laundering, specifically in connection with drug trafficking. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of drug-related proceeds and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: This convention expanded the scope of money laundering offenses to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes, not just drug trafficking. It also promotes international cooperation in combating transnational organized crime, including money laundering.\n\n*   **International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999)**: This convention requires states to criminalize the financing of terrorism and to take measures to prevent and counter the financing of terrorism, including through money laundering laws and regulations.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**: The FATF is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. Its 40 Recommendations are the internationally recognized standards for combating these threats and are widely adopted by countries around the world. While the FATF Recommendations themselves are not legally binding treaties, they exert significant influence because countries are assessed on their compliance with these standards, and non-compliance can have serious consequences.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (CETS No. 198)**: This convention, also known as the Warsaw Convention, aims to strengthen measures to prevent and combat money laundering and the financing of terrorism through criminal law and international cooperation.\n\n*   **European Union Directives**: The European Union has issued several directives on money laundering and terrorist financing that are binding on EU member states. These directives establish minimum standards for national laws and regulations on these matters.\n\nThese international laws and standards have significantly shaped national anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations in countries around the world. They have contributed to the establishment of AML frameworks, the creation of FIUs, and the promotion of international cooperation in combating money laundering and related crimes.",
